<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare='numbers'>$zero </award>
</answer>
</p>

<p>Under what conditions are there no equilibria? <m>b =</m> 
<answer>
<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare='numbers'>$one </award>
</answer>
 and <m>c \ne</m> 
<answer>
<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare='numbers'>$zero </award>
</answer>
</p>



</li>

<li>
<p>
How does the stability of the equilibria depend on the values of the parameter <m>b</m> and <m>c</m>?
</p>
<p>

The equilibrium is stable for 
<answer>
<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare='numbers'>$n1 </award>
</answer>
 <m>\lt b \lt</m> 
<answer>
<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare='numbers'>$one </award>
</answer>

</p>
<p>

The equilibrium is unstable for <m>b \gt</m> 
<answer>
<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare='numbers'>$one </award>
</answer>
 or <m>b \lt</m> 
<answer>
<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare='numbers'>$n1 </award>
</answer>

</p>
<p>

The stability of the equilibrium 
<answer inline='true'>
<choiceinput>
<choice credit='1'>does not</choice>
<choice>does</choice>
</choiceinput>
</answer>
 depend on the value of <m>c</m>.
</p>
<p>

In these cases, the one equilibrium is <m>E=</m> 
<answer>
<award>$E </award>
</answer>

</p>

<p>We have some special cases that are missed by the above conditions. 
<ul>
<li>For <m>b=</m> 
<answer>
<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare='numbers'>$n1 </award>
</answer>
, the solution spirals around the one equilibrium at <m>E=</m> 
<answer>
<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare='numbers'>$E </award>
<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare='numbers'>$E_b_n1 </award>
</answer>
.  Since the solution 
<answer inline='true'>
<choiceinput>
<choice credit='1'>does not</choice>
<choice>does</choice>
</choiceinput>
</answer>
 get further away from the equilibrium, we still say the equilibrium is 
<answer inline='true'>
<choiceinput>
<choice credit='1'>stable</choice>
<choice>unstable</choice>
</choiceinput>
</answer>
.</li>

<li>For <m>b=</m> 
<answer>
<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare='numbers'>$one </award>
</answer>
 and <m>c=</m> 
<answer>
<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare='numbers'>$zero </award>
</answer>
, there are an infinite number of equilibria.  However, since the solution 
<answer inline='true'>
<choiceinput>
<choice credit='1'>does not</choice>
<choice>does</choice>
</choiceinput>
</answer>
 move for any initial condition, the solution 
<answer inline='true'>
<choiceinput>
<choice credit='1'>does not</choice>
<choice>does</choice>
</choiceinput>
</answer>
 get further away from any equilibrium.  Therefore, we still say each equilibrium is 
<answer inline='true'>
<choiceinput>
<choice credit='1'>stable</choice>
<choice>unstable</choice>
</choiceinput>
</answer>
.</li>

<li>Since for <m>b=</m> 
<answer>
<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare='numbers'>$one </award>
</answer>
 and <m>c \ne</m> 
<answer>
<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare='numbers'>$zero </award>
</answer>
