</p>

</li>


</ol>


<solution>


<ol>

<li>
If <m>b \ne 1</m>, there is exactly one equilibrium, <m>E=c/(1-b)</m>.  The value of this equilibrium does depend on the value of both <m>b</m> and <m>c</m>.

<p>If <m>b=1</m> and <m>c=0</m>, there are an infinite number of equilibria.</p>
<p>If <m>b=1</m> and <m>c \ne 0</m>, there are no equilibria.</p>
</li>

<li>
Th equilibrium is stable for <m>-1 \lt b \lt 1</m>.  It is unstable for <m>b \gt 1</m> or <m>b \lt -1</m>.  The stability does not depend on the value of <m>c</m>.  The equilibrium in these cases is <m>E=c/(1-b)</m>.

<ul>
<li>For <m>b=-1</m>, the solution spirals around the one equilibrium at <m>E=c/(1-b)=c/2</m> .  Since the solution does not get further away from the equilibrium, we still say the equilibrium is stable.</li>

<li>For <m>b=1</m> and <m>c=0</m>, there are an infinite number of equilibria.  However, since the solution does not move for any initial condition, the solution does not get further away from any equilibrium.  Therefore, we still say each equilibrium is stable.</li>

<li>Since for <m>b=1</m> and <m>c \ne 0</m>, there are no equilibria, it doesn't make sense to discuss stability.</li>

</ul>
</li>

<li>
<p>
When <m>b</m> is negative, the solution spirals around the equilibrium.
</p>
<p>

When <m>b</m> is positive, the solution moves steadily toward or away from the equilibrium.
</p>
<p>

The behavior of the solution does not depend on the sign of <m>c</m>
</p>
</li>


</ol>

</solution>


</problem>